>>46023426
Having written a few and with a couple more in drafts, get that first draft done asap.
Editing and typesetting for a proper print edition is a skillset that most people here won't be able to do. 90% of your work is at that stage.
No matter how good you think you are, several passes for continuity and the like will teach you that your attention to detail isn't what you thought.

Also, print gets expensive quick. Choosing between comfy scenes and active plot really changes your writing style.

But if you start and don't give up, it will make you a much better and disciplined writer.

I've always found arranged marriages between nobles absolutely fascinating. It's easy to see the bad in it, and I am not denying it, but to me it is a whole other romantic experience; knowing that the person you have to spend the rest of your life with, the person who will bear your children and the person you are to grow old with was introduced to you because of political reason, a favour for a friend or some sort of deal.

It's just so different to someone who is used to slowly building up to a relationship with a person, getting to know them, gradually spending more time together. The dynamic is familiar. I do wonder what it'd be like to meet my wife literally a few months before a wedding, and having to work through the getting-to-know each other part while you are already bound together and, if you are to produce heirs, frequently fucking.

And having the bethrothed be a member of a completely different species, having to work through all the unfamiliar anatomy, cultural and species-specific customs, getting used to the unfamilar feelings of your completely different bodies. Despite this being a thread for xenophiles, I imagine most people in the world would stick to their own species, and so being forced into marriage with an anthro for political reasons gives it an extra strangely romantic air.
If I was a writefag I would totally write something like this. Especially the 'getting to know each other's unfamilar bodies' part - after all, the kingdom needs an heir.

I am fully aware that this is clearly romanticizing it and more than likely it leads to marital issues, infidelity and unhappy marriages bound only by church scrutiny - but isn't everything we discuss a 'best case scenario' anyway?
